e-wrap-foot><fn id="dom12427-note-0001"><p>
<styled-content style="fixed-case">HbA1c</styled-content>, glycated haemoglobin. Data are mean &#x000b1; standard deviation unless otherwise indicated.</p></fn><fn id="dom12427-note-0002"><label>*</label><p>All with <styled-content style="fixed-case">C</styled-content>&#x02010;peptide levels lower than 33 pmol/l.</p></fn></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap></sec><sec id="dom12427-sec-0016"><title>Primary and Secondary Outcomes Overnight</title><p id="dom12427-para-0022">The primary endpoint, the proportion of time when overnight sensor glucose levels were in the target range, was significantly increased by a mean of 18.4% [95% confidence interval (CI) 13.5&#x02013;23.4%; p &#x0003c; 0.001] during closed&#x02010;loop therapy (Table <xref rid="dom12427-tbl-0002" ref-type="table-wrap">2</xref>). Closed&#x02010;loop therapy significantly reduced mean overnight sensor glucose by 0.9 mmol/l (95% CI 0.4&#x02013;1.3 mmol/l; p &#x0003c; 0.001), as well as the proportion of time when sensor glucose values were in hyperglycaemia (&#x0003e;8.0 mmol/l; mean 15.9%, 95% CI 10.7&#x02013;21.0%; p &#x0003c; 0.001) and hypoglycaemia (&#x0003c;3.9 mmol/l; median 0.9%, 95% CI 0.2&#x02013;2.2; p = 0.014; Table <xref rid="dom12427-tbl-0002" ref-type="table-wrap">2</xref>, Figure <xref rid="dom12427-fig-0001" ref-type="fig">1</xref>). There was no significant difference in the burden of hypoglycaemia as measured by the area under the curve when sensor glucose levels were &#x0003c;3.5 mmol/l (p = 0.15).</p><table-wrap id="dom12427-tbl-0002" xml:lang="en" orientation="portrait" position="float"><label>Table 2</label><caption><p>Intention&#x02010;to&#x02010;treat comparison of glucose outcomes from 24:00 to 08:00 hours during overnight closed&#x02010;loop therapy and the control period in the home setting over 3&#x02013;4 weeks</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="left" span="1"/><thead val